---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Bindings — how you embed the engine" description="The three layers of tflo: core engine, language bindings, and the applications built on top. What ships today and what is on the roadmap.">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-16">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold text-white mb-2">Bindings</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-text-muted mb-12">How you embed the engine in a host environment.</p>

    <!-- Three layers -->
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4">Three distinct layers</h2>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      These layers are separate concerns. Do not conflate them.
    </p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-border mb-8">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-card">
            <th class="text-left p-4 font-semibold text-white">Layer</th>
            <th class="text-left p-4 font-semibold text-white">What it is</th>
            <th class="text-left p-4 font-semibold text-white">Crates</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="text-text-muted">
          <tr class="border-b border-border hover:bg-bg-card transition-colors">
            <td class="p-4 text-white font-medium">Core engine</td>
            <td class="p-4">The pure temporal engine &mdash; computation graph, windowing, timers, typed absence, event-time semantics, CEP pattern matching, and the operator catalog. No I/O, no host assumptions.</td>
            <td class="p-4"><code class="text-primary">tflo-core</code>, <code class="text-primary">tflo-cep</code>, <code class="text-primary">tflo-ops</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-border hover:bg-bg-card transition-colors">
            <td class="p-4 text-white font-medium">Bindings / runtimes</td>
            <td class="p-4">How you embed the engine in a specific host: native Rust crate, WebAssembly module, or (on the roadmap) a foreign-language binding. Each binding exposes the engine's semantics in idiomatic form for its target.</td>
            <td class="p-4"><code class="text-primary">tflo-wasm</code>, <code class="text-primary">tflo-cep-wasm</code>, (native: direct)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hover:bg-bg-card transition-colors">
            <td class="p-4 text-white font-medium">Examples / applications</td>
            <td class="p-4">Concrete things built on a binding: a React temporal UX, a browser analytics library, an edge gateway, a backtesting harness. They are built <em>on top of</em> a binding; they do not define it.</td>
            <td class="p-4"><a href="/positioning" class="text-primary hover:underline">React UX</a>, <a href="/docs/browser-analytics" class="text-primary hover:underline">browser-events</a>, …</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- Native Rust -->
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4">Native Rust binding</h2>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      Embed <code>tflo-core</code> directly as a Rust dependency. There is no separate binding crate
      for native Rust &mdash; the core <em>is</em> the binding. You get the full
      <code>Iterator::tflo</code> and <code>Stream::tflo</code> surface, keyed execution,
      snapshot/restore, and the complete operator catalog from <code>tflo-ops</code>.
    </p>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      Suitable for: edge gateways, server-side services (tonic / axum / actix), batch pipelines,
      and backtesting harnesses. Compiles to ARM and musl targets; heap footprint is proportional
      to window state, not to a runtime. Ships today.
    </p>

    <!-- WASM -->
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4">WebAssembly binding</h2>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      The engine compiled to WebAssembly for JavaScript and TypeScript hosts. Two crates cover
      the two engine surfaces:
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-text-muted mb-6">
      <li>
        <strong class="text-white">tflo-wasm</strong> &mdash; the windowing and operator layer
        (<code>tflo-core</code> + <code>tflo-ops</code>), exposed as a JS module.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-white">tflo-cep-wasm</strong> &mdash; the complex-event pattern engine
        (<code>tflo-cep</code>), exposed for JS/TS consumers.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      This WASM layer is the substrate under <em>both</em> browser examples &mdash; the
      <a href="/positioning" class="text-primary hover:underline">React temporal UX</a> and the
      <a href="/docs/browser-analytics" class="text-primary hover:underline">browser analytics</a>
      library. The engine is not married to React, to any framework, or to any particular JS
      packaging. The two examples are independent applications that happen to share the same WASM
      binding. Ships today.
    </p>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      Cross-tier parity follows directly: because the server runs native Rust and the browser runs
      the same engine compiled to WASM, both evaluate the same rule against the same event log and
      produce the same output. This is not "same algorithm reimplemented twice" &mdash; it is the
      same compiled artifact, different ABI.
    </p>

    <!-- Roadmap -->
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4">Other languages &mdash; roadmap</h2>
    <div class="p-5 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/40 bg-amber-500/5 mb-6">
      <p class="text-text-muted">
        <strong class="text-white">Roadmap, not shipped.</strong> C#, Go, and Python bindings do
        not exist today. Native Rust and WASM are what ship.
      </p>
    </div>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      A pure, deterministic engine with no runtime assumptions ports cleanly across language
      runtimes. The same property that makes cross-tier parity tractable for Rust/WASM makes
      cross-language parity tractable more broadly: the engine is a function of the event log
      and the rule, with no ambient state. The bindings differ; the semantics do not.
    </p>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
      Likely paths: C# and Go via WASM (same artifact, different host); Python via WASM or
      PyO3 FFI. The ordering and exact mechanism are not settled. If you have a concrete need,
      file an issue on the crate's repository.
    </p>

    <!-- Next -->
    <div class="mt-16 p-6 rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-card">
      <p class="text-text-muted">
        <strong class="text-white">See also:</strong>{' '}
        <a href="/docs/examples" class="text-primary hover:underline">Examples</a>
        {' '}&mdash; concrete applications built on the native and WASM bindings &mdash; and{' '}
        <a href="/positioning" class="text-primary hover:underline">Positioning</a>
        {' '}for the React temporal UX walkthrough, or{' '}
        <a href="/docs/browser-analytics" class="text-primary hover:underline">browser analytics</a>
        {' '}for the framework-agnostic browser example.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
